Oh, no, it's not hard to believe.

234
00:20:21,119 --> 00:20:23,480
It's a good racket, Poldek.
The only racket here.

235
00:20:23,559 --> 00:20:26,839
Look, maybe I could put in a good
word for you with my superiors.

236
00:20:26,880 --> 00:20:31,000
Your superiors? Come on, they
are not as bad as everyone says.

237
00:20:31,079 --> 00:20:34,160
Well, they're worse than everyone
says, but it's a lot of money.

238
00:20:34,240 --> 00:20:36,759
A lot of money.

239
00:20:36,799 --> 00:20:39,480
Give me my
housing assignment.

240
00:20:39,559 --> 00:20:43,799
Come on. You look funny
in that hat, Goldberg.

241
00:20:43,880 --> 00:20:47,119
You look like a clown,
you know?

242
00:20:51,839 --> 00:20:54,200
He's a very important man.

243
00:20:54,240 --> 00:20:55,960
Just give him
two minutes of your time.

244
00:20:56,039 --> 00:20:59,279
Since when did time cost money?
Just sit down and listen.

245
00:20:59,359 --> 00:21:01,519
Please.
Sir?

246
00:21:05,079 --> 00:21:07,039
For each thousand you invest,
I will repay you with...

247
00:21:07,079 --> 00:21:09,200
Two hundred. 200 kilos
of enamelware a month,

248
00:21:09,240 --> 00:21:11,119
to begin in July and to
continue for one year.

249
00:21:11,200 --> 00:21:14,799
After which time, we're even.
That's it. It's very simple.

250
00:21:14,880 --> 00:21:17,680
Not good enough. It's not good enough.

251
00:21:17,759 --> 00:21:19,920
Not good enough?

252
00:21:19,960 --> 00:21:23,920
Look where you're living. Look where
you've been put. "Not good enough. "

253
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:26,440
A couple of months ago you'd
be right, not anymore.

254
00:21:26,519 --> 00:21:29,519
Money's still money.

255
00:21:31,039 --> 00:21:33,200
No, it is not.

256
00:21:33,240 --> 00:21:35,279
That's why we're here.

257
00:21:35,359 --> 00:21:37,240
Trade goods...
that's the only currency...

258
00:21:37,279 --> 00:21:39,160
that'll be worth
anything in the ghetto.

259
00:21:39,200 --> 00:21:42,480
Things have changed,
my friend.

260
00:21:43,200 --> 00:21:45,519
Did I call
this meeting?

261
00:21:45,599 --> 00:21:47,880
You told Mr. Stern
you wanted to speak to me.

262
00:21:47,960 --> 00:21:50,480
I'm here.
I've made you a fair offer.

263
00:21:50,559 --> 00:21:54,319
Fair would be
a percentage in the company.

264
00:21:54,400 --> 00:21:57,519
Forget the whole thing.

265
00:21:57,559 --> 00:21:59,759
Get out.

266
00:22:03,839 --> 00:22:06,759
How do we know that you
will do what you say?

267
00:22:06,839 --> 00:22:08,680
Because I said I would.

268
00:22:08,759 --> 00:22:10,880
You want a contract?
To be upheld by what court?

269
00:22:10,960 --> 00:22:13,799
I said what I'll do.
That's our contract.

270
00:22:17,079 --> 00:22:19,119
...mielismy racje.

271
00:22:30,359 --> 00:22:35,599
Piec, szesc, siedem...

272
00:22:35,680 --> 00:22:39,119
osiem, dziewiec.

273
00:22:50,160 --> 00:22:54,279
The standard SS rate for Jewish
skilled labor is seven marks a day,

274
00:22:54,319 --> 00:22:57,160
five for unskilled
and women.

275
00:22:57,200 --> 00:23:00,160
This is what you pay
the Reich Economic Office.

276
00:23:00,240 --> 00:23:02,640
TheJews themselves
receive nothing.

277
00:23:02,720 --> 00:23:06,960
Poles you pay wages. Generally,
they get a little more.

278
00:23:07,039 --> 00:23:09,480
Are you listening? What
was that about the SS?

279
00:23:09,559 --> 00:23:11,759
The rate? The what?

280
00:23:11,839 --> 00:23:15,279
TheJewish worker's salary... you pay it
directly to the SS, not to the worker.

281
00:23:15,319 --> 00:23:17,359
He gets nothing.
But it's less.

282
00:23:17,440 --> 00:23:19,440
It's less than what I
would pay a Pole. It's less.

283
00:23:19,519 --> 00:23:22,319
That's the point
I'm trying to make.

284
00:23:22,400 --> 00:23:24,880
Poles cost more.

285
00:23:24,960 --> 00:23:29,359
Why should I hire Poles?

286
00:23:29,440 --> 00:23:33,200
An enamelware factory
over at, uh, Lipowa Street.

287
00:23:33,279 --> 00:23:36,079
It, uh, it, um...
It's owned by a German.

288
00:23:36,160 --> 00:23:39,160
But it's outside the ghetto, so
you can barter for extra goods...

289
00:23:39,200 --> 00:23:41,359
for eggs, I don't know
what you need...

290
00:23:41,400 --> 00:23:43,440
with the Polish workers.
You can't get it here.

291
00:23:43,519 --> 00:23:47,599
Also, he's asking for ten healthy
women for the... I am healthy.

292
00:23:47,680 --> 00:23:50,559
Bring your sister, okay?

293
00:23:54,720 --> 00:23:57,039
Chodz.

294
00:23:57,079 --> 00:24:00,359
You need to convince them you have a
trade, something valuable to the war effort.

295
00:24:00,440 --> 00:24:02,599
Like what? What if you
don't? I'm a musician.

296
00:24:02,680 --> 00:24:06,119
Your name goes on a list.
And they put you on trucks...

297
00:24:06,200 --> 00:24:08,240
No, no, no, that's not
true. You're a musician?

298
00:24:08,319 --> 00:24:10,720
Yeah. I'd find a good
hiding place if I were you.

299
00:24:10,799 --> 00:24:15,079
I'm not going to hide like some
animal. There are places to hide.

300
00:24:19,519 --> 00:24:21,359
Der Naechste!

301
00:24:21,440 --> 00:24:24,680
I'm a graduate
of the University of Lwow.

302
00:24:24,759 --> 00:24:27,880
I used to work at the
hydroelectric station in Roznow...

303
00:24:27,960 --> 00:24:29,799
Blauschein.

304
00:24:32,920 --> 00:24:36,680
I'm gonna get the necessary papers
because this card is no good anymore.

305
00:24:36,759 --> 00:24:39,079
You can stay in this line all
day, you'll still get one of these.

306
00:24:39,160 --> 00:24:42,759
They are no good. You'll
have to leave the line now,

307
00:24:42,839 --> 00:24:47,240
then you'll get a blue card, a Blauschein,
to say that you are an essential worker.

308
00:24:47,319 --> 00:24:50,279
I'll get these papers
for you at Pankiewicz.

309
00:24:50,359 --> 00:24:52,279
Pharmacist.
Just there, look.

310
00:24:52,359 --> 00:24:54,200
Guess who is here?

311
00:24:54,240 --> 00:24:56,839
Poldek! Enjoying
the weather, Poldek?

312
00:24:56,920 --> 00:24:59,799
Enjoying the lines?
Need some shoe polish?

313
00:24:59,839 --> 00:25:02,279
In a metal container
maybe?

314
00:25:02,359 --> 00:25:06,640
Not essential? I think you
misunderstand the meaning of the word.

315
00:25:06,720 --> 00:25:09,519
No Blauschein, sir.
Stand over there.

316
00:25:09,559 --> 00:25:12,240
Move. Next!

317
00:25:12,319 --> 00:25:14,519
What do you mean,
"Not essential"?

318
00:25:14,599 --> 00:25:20,079
I teach history and literature.
Since when is not essential?

319
00:25:25,119 --> 00:25:27,480
He's a metal polisher.

320
00:25:34,079 --> 00:25:36,759
It was not right? It's very
good. He's 53 years old.

321
00:25:36,799 --> 00:25:39,799
It's too new. Mmm. Thank you.

322
00:25:47,680 --> 00:25:50,039
You're crazy. You
left it in your drawer.

323
00:25:50,119 --> 00:25:52,279
How many times
have I told you?

324
00:25:52,319 --> 00:25:54,960
Your work certificate you keep
in your pocket at all times.

325
00:25:55,039 --> 00:25:56,920
And you leave everything
in your drawer.

326
00:25:56,960 --> 00:25:59,279
How many times I've told you?

327
00:25:59,359 --> 00:26:02,480
I'm a metal polisher.

328
00:26:10,880 --> 00:26:13,400
Take the round sheet of tin,

329
00:26:13,440 --> 00:26:17,200
dip it in soap emulsion.

330
00:26:17,279 --> 00:26:22,160
Then place it centrally
in the press.

331
00:26:36,799 --> 00:26:40,039
We obtain the soup pot.
The soup pot.

332
00:26:40,079 --> 00:26:43,359
Soup pot.

333
00:26:43,440 --> 00:26:46,480
Grosz, Mrs. Grosz,
stay together.

334
00:26:50,519 --> 00:26:55,519
Sir, I have ten work permits here
for the Deutsche Emailwarenfabrik,

335
00:26:55,599 --> 00:26:58,319
cosigned by Mr. Bankier
and myself.

336
00:26:58,400 --> 00:27:02,880
If it's carbonized,
clean it with a file.

337
00:27:02,960 --> 00:27:07,519
But don't touch both the
electrodes at the same time.

338
00:27:07,599 --> 00:27:10,680
You'll get electrocuted.
Here, have a try.

339
00:27:14,799 --> 00:27:17,119
Roll the metal
under the press,

340
00:27:17,200 --> 00:27:19,519
but be very careful
unless you want your fingers...

341
00:27:19,599 --> 00:27:22,319
to become part
of the teapot.

342
00:27:23,839 --> 00:27:27,359
Occupation? I'm a
writer. I play the flute.

343
00:27:27,440 --> 00:27:30,720
But Moses is
a skilled metalworker.

344
00:27:30,799 --> 00:27:32,960
He can make tin pots.
He can make tanks.

345
00:27:33,039 --> 00:27:34,880
He can make whatever
Mr. Schindler asks.

346
00:27:34,960 --> 00:27:37,440
He's highly skilled.
Give him your card.

347
00:27:37,519 --> 00:27:39,839
Moses, give him your card.

348
00:27:41,799 --> 00:27:44,000
Now, dip the basin
with the tongs...

349
00:27:44,079 --> 00:27:46,519
into the enamel solution.

350
00:27:48,480 --> 00:27:52,720
And after swiveling it around,
carefully place it aside to drip dry.

351
00:27:55,640 --> 00:27:58,920
And whatever he asks you, allow me
just to represent you and speak for you.

352
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:00,960
Don't say a word.

353
00:28:01,039 --> 00:28:04,359
Filing, billing, keeping track
of my appointments, shorthand.

354
00:28:04,440 --> 00:28:08,559
Typing, obviously. How is
your typing? Uh, all right.

355
00:28:08,640 --> 00:28:10,480
Please.

356
00:29:01,200 --> 00:29:04,720
You need a secretary.
Pick one.

357
00:29:04,799 --> 00:29:09,519
I don't know how. They're
all so... qualified.

358
00:29:09,599 --> 00:29:12,400
You have to choose.

359
00:29:14,640 --> 00:29:17,319
Prosze sie ladnie usmiechac.
Big smile. Big smile.

360
00:29:17,359 --> 00:29:18,720
Uwaga.

361
00:29:37,400 --> 00:29:40,240
If you would,
look after my guest.

362
00:29:40,279 --> 00:29:45,400
Um, boxed teas are good.
Coffee, pate, um...

363
00:29:45,440 --> 00:29:49,480
kielbasa sausage, cheeses,
Beluga caviar. Yes.

364
00:29:49,519 --> 00:29:51,279
And, of course, who could live
without German cigarettes?

365
00:29:51,359 --> 00:29:53,480
Get me as many
as you can find.

366
00:29:53,559 --> 00:29:55,559
And some more fresh fruit.

367
00:29:55,640 --> 00:29:58,319
The real rarities...
oranges, lemons, pineapples.

368
00:29:58,400 --> 00:30:01,000
I need several boxes of
Cuban cigars. The best. Yes.

369
00:30:01,079 --> 00:30:04,680
And dark, unsweetened chocolate. Not in the
shape ofladyfingers, the chunk chocolate.

370
00:30:04,759 --> 00:30:07,799
Yes. Big as my hand, you
sample at wine tastings.

371
00:30:07,880 --> 00:30:10,920
We're going to need lots
of cognac. The best, Hennessy.

372
00:30:10,960 --> 00:30:16,200
Dom Perignon champagne.
Um, get L 'espadon sardines...

373
00:30:16,279 --> 00:30:19,119
and, oh,
try to find nylon stockings.

374
00:30:21,559 --> 00:30:24,680
It is my distinct pleasure
to announce...

375
00:30:24,759 --> 00:30:30,119
the fully operational status
of Deutsche Email Fabrik...

376
00:30:30,200 --> 00:30:31,400
Patrzjakies szmaty!

377
00:30:31,440 --> 00:30:34,759
Manufacturers of superior
enamelware crockery...

378
00:30:34,839 --> 00:30:40,039
expressly designed
and crafted for military use.

379
00:30:40,119 --> 00:30:42,640
Utilizing only
the most modern equipment,

380
00:30:42,720 --> 00:30:47,599
D.E.F. 's staff of highly-skilled and
experienced artisans andjourneymen...

381
00:30:47,680 --> 00:30:51,079
deliver a product
of unparalleled quality,

382
00:30:51,160 --> 00:30:54,960
enabling me to proffer, with
absolute confidence and pride,

383
00:30:55,039 --> 00:30:57,519
a full line
of field and kitchenware...

384
00:30:57,599 --> 00:31:01,519
unsurpassable in all respects
by my competitors.

385
00:31:01,599 --> 00:31:04,160
See attached list
and available colors.

386
00:31:04,240 --> 00:31:08,839
Anticipating the enclosed bids
will meet with your approval.

387
00:31:08,880 --> 00:31:12,559
Made in Havana, Cuba. Looking forward to
a long and mutually prosperous association.

388
00:31:12,640 --> 00:31:15,799
Look at this. I extend to you in
advance my sincerest gratitude...

389
00:31:15,839 --> 00:31:18,680
and very best regards.
Oskar Schindler.

390
00:31:18,720 --> 00:31:22,000
Yeah, I need 700 gross
from here for next Thursday.

391
00:31:22,079 --> 00:31:24,720
Nine hundred... No, make
it ten for Wednesday.

392
00:31:24,799 --> 00:31:28,519
All this stuff here goes to Madritsch's
factory on Tuesday of next week.

393
00:31:43,640 --> 00:31:46,960
My father was fond of saying,
"You need three things in life:

394
00:31:47,039 --> 00:31:50,920
"A good doctor,
a forgiving priest...

395
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:54,160
and a clever accountant. "

396
00:31:57,440 --> 00:32:01,279
The first two...
I've never had much use for.

397
00:32:01,359 --> 00:32:04,720
But the third...

398
00:32:09,720 --> 00:32:13,079
Just pretend,
for Christ's sake.

399
00:32:16,599 --> 00:32:19,759
Is that all?

400
00:32:24,319 --> 00:32:27,440
I'm trying to thank you.

401
00:32:27,480 --> 00:32:31,480
I'm saying I couldn't
have done this without you.

402
00:32:33,920 --> 00:32:36,720
The usual thing would be
to acknowledge my gratitude.

403
00:32:36,799 --> 00:32:41,440
It would also, by the way,
be the courteous thing.

404
00:32:41,480 --> 00:32:44,240
You're welcome.

405
00:32:52,759 --> 00:32:54,960
Get out of here.

406
00:33:07,720 --> 00:33:10,839
Klonowska, who is it?

407
00:33:19,759 --> 00:33:22,359
She's so embarrassed.
Look at her.

408
00:33:33,839 --> 00:33:36,079
You know something?
You would like her.

409
00:33:36,119 --> 00:33:38,000
Oskar, please.
What?

410
00:33:38,039 --> 00:33:40,400
I don't have to like her... just
because you do. You would, though.

411
00:33:40,480 --> 00:33:43,119
It doesn't
work that way.

412
00:33:55,359 --> 00:33:58,160
You've done well here.

413
00:34:00,440 --> 00:34:02,920
You look wonderful.

414
00:34:05,680 --> 00:34:09,039
Be careful of the step,
miss. Mrs. Schindler, Marek.

415
00:34:21,239 --> 00:34:25,039
It's not a charade, all this?
How could it be a charade?

416
00:34:25,119 --> 00:34:27,400
The clothes, the car, the
apartment. Wait a minute.

417
00:34:27,480 --> 00:34:31,280
Take a guess how many people
are on my payroll. Oskar.

418
00:34:31,320 --> 00:34:36,840
My father, at the height of his
success, had 50. I've got 350.

419
00:34:36,880 --> 00:34:41,000
350 workers on the factory
floor, with one purpose.

420
00:34:41,079 --> 00:34:43,199
To make pots and pans?

421
00:34:43,280 --> 00:34:47,079
To make money.
For me.

422
00:34:52,559 --> 00:34:55,679
Does anyone
ask about me?

423
00:34:57,079 --> 00:35:00,199
Back home?
Everybody.

424
00:35:00,239 --> 00:35:03,079
All the time.

425
00:35:03,119 --> 00:35:06,280
Hmm.

426
00:35:06,360 --> 00:35:11,719
They won't soon forget the name
Schindler here, I can tell you that.

427
00:35:13,079 --> 00:35:16,199
"Oskar Schindler,"
they'll say.

428
00:35:16,239 --> 00:35:19,559
"Everybody
remembers him.

429
00:35:19,639 --> 00:35:23,880
"He did something
extraordinary.

430
00:35:23,960 --> 00:35:28,840
"He did something
no one else did.

431
00:35:28,920 --> 00:35:32,079
"He came here
with nothing...

432
00:35:32,159 --> 00:35:34,960
"a suitcase...

433
00:35:35,039 --> 00:35:40,400
"and built a bankrupt company
into a major manufactory.

434
00:35:40,480 --> 00:35:43,960
"And left with
a steamer trunk...

435
00:35:44,039 --> 00:35:48,440
"Two steamer trunks
full of money,

436
00:35:48,480 --> 00:35:52,559
all the riches
of the world. "

437
00:35:52,639 --> 00:35:54,480
Hmm.

438
00:35:54,559 --> 00:35:57,719
It's comforting to see
that nothing's changed.

439
00:35:57,760 --> 00:36:01,199
You're wrong, Emilie.

440
00:36:01,280 --> 00:36:03,639
There's no way I could have
known this before,

441
00:36:03,679 --> 00:36:07,000
but there was always
something missing.

442
00:36:07,039 --> 00:36:11,000
In every business I tried, I can
see now, it wasn't me that failed.

443
00:36:11,079 --> 00:36:13,719
Something was missing.

444
00:36:13,760 --> 00:36:17,199
Even if I'd known what it was, there's
nothing I could have done about it...

445
00:36:17,280 --> 00:36:21,679
because you can't
create this thing.

446
00:36:21,760 --> 00:36:26,840
And it makes all the difference in
the world between success and failure.

447
00:36:26,880 --> 00:36:29,320
Luck?

448
00:36:31,679 --> 00:36:34,480
War.

449
00:36:56,960 --> 00:37:00,559
Should I stay?

450
00:37:00,639 --> 00:37:05,199
It's a beautiful city.

451
00:37:05,280 --> 00:37:10,000
I asked you
if I should stay.

452
00:37:10,079 --> 00:37:12,960
It's up to you.

453
00:37:16,760 --> 00:37:21,199
Promise me, Oskar, no doorman
or maitre d' will ever presume...

454
00:37:21,280 --> 00:37:26,400
I'm anyone other than Mrs.
Schindler, and I'll stay.

455
00:37:28,559 --> 00:37:30,719
Good-bye, darling.

456
00:37:46,639 --> 00:37:50,719
I could try to read this or I could
eat my lunch while it's still hot.

457
00:37:50,800 --> 00:37:52,679
We're doing well?

458
00:37:52,760 --> 00:37:54,000
Yes. Better this month than last?

459
00:37:54,039 --> 00:37:56,199
Yes. Any reason to think
next month will be worse?

460
00:37:56,239 --> 00:37:59,360
The war could end.

461
00:38:08,880 --> 00:38:11,360
What? There is a machinist outside...

462
00:38:11,440 --> 00:38:14,400
who'd like to thank you
personally for giving him a job.

463
00:38:14,480 --> 00:38:19,000
Every day he comes. He's very
grateful. It'll just take a minute.

464
00:38:25,039 --> 00:38:27,320
Mr. Lowenstein?

465
00:38:34,000 --> 00:38:36,960
I want to thank you, sir,

466
00:38:37,039 --> 00:38:39,679
for giving me
the opportunity to work.

467
00:38:39,760 --> 00:38:42,559
You're welcome. I'm sure
you're doing a great job.

468
00:38:42,639 --> 00:38:46,760
The SS beat me up.
They would have killed me,

469
00:38:46,840 --> 00:38:51,360
but I am essential to the
war effort, thanks to you.

470
00:38:51,400 --> 00:38:53,280
That's great.

471
00:38:53,320 --> 00:38:55,880
I work hard for you.

472
